4:T9e0,<p>The typical Indian startup's approach to international commercial expansion goes like this: find the problem, raise the capital, hire a country head. Then wait six months for them to start. Then wait another six months before knowing if it was the right hire.</p>

<p>That model made sense when the cost of a bad hire was an acceptable risk. It no longer does — not at the pace at which Indian startups are now expected to produce international revenue.</p>

<h2>The actual problem isn't hiring capacity. It's network access.</h2>

<p>Commercial success in international markets — whether it's the UK, the US, Southeast Asia, or the GCC — is disproportionately driven by relationships. Who you know in a buyer organisation. Which channel partner will take your call. Which regional distributor has the trust of local enterprises.</p>

<p>A full-time hire can build those relationships. Over time. At great expense. With no guarantee.</p>

<p>A senior fractional professional who spent the last decade in that market already has them. The question isn't whether they can build relationships — it's whether you can give them a structured, compensated, scoped reason to deploy those relationships on your behalf.</p>

<h2>Why fractional structures solve this</h2>

<p>Fractional engagement models — retainers, sprints, success-fee structures — change the economics of senior talent access fundamentally. A company that cannot justify a $200,000 annual salary for a VP of Sales can often justify $7,500/month for 20 hours/week of a professional with better networks, more relevant experience, and clearer accountability.</p>

<p>The math works. The model works. What's been missing is the infrastructure: the vetting, the matching, the contracting, the compliance, the milestone tracking. That infrastructure is what BridgeScale provides.</p>

<h2>What "fractional" actually means in practice</h2>

<p>It does not mean part-time advisory calls. It means a defined scope of work, documented deliverables, milestone-gated payments, and regular accountability cadence. It means someone who is professionally responsible for outcomes — not just inputs.</p>

<p>Done correctly, a fractional senior commercial engagement can deliver more in 90 days than a full-time hire in 12 months — because the talent is senior enough to know what matters, experienced enough to execute without a learning curve, and incentivised enough to produce results rather than just show up.</p>

<p>That's the model. That's why it works.</p>6:["slug","why-fractional-commercial-talent-works-for-indian-startups","d"]
